WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.760
Our next speaker represents the year 2018.

00:00:03.760 --> 00:00:08.120
And his current favorite spirit is Rum Fire.

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:10.280
Please welcome Hadley.

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:11.360
Hey, everyone.

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:16.400
So today, I wanted to talk about putting R in production.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:20.080
And this is a talk about a topic I don't really

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:21.520
know anything about.

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:23.360
And I've never done it myself.

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:26.559
So a lot of this, I'm not going to be showing you any code

00:00:26.559 --> 00:00:27.320
today.

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:28.820
What I'm going to be showing you is

00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:32.020
my efforts to understand what this thing is all about,

00:00:32.020 --> 00:00:34.580
with the hope that a few months down the road,

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:38.020
it'll start to maybe influence some open source packages

00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:41.180
or maybe some of Posit's pro tools.

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:42.580
And I also want to say, I'm going

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:47.020
to be talking about R in lowercase p production,

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:50.619
not R in uppercase p production.

00:00:50.619 --> 00:00:52.700
And I think this is an important distinction

00:00:52.700 --> 00:00:57.580
to make if you're talking to folks in your IT organization

00:00:57.580 --> 00:00:59.020
or your DevOps organization.

00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:00.480
Because when they think production,

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:03.779
they're often going to think capital P production.

00:01:03.779 --> 00:01:06.339
And what's the difference?

00:01:06.339 --> 00:01:12.500
The difference, I think, is basically paging.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:19.019
And that is strange.

00:01:19.019 --> 00:01:21.300
I am seeing something different to what you are seeing.

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:24.099
OK.

00:01:24.099 --> 00:01:25.180
The difference is paging.

00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:27.860
So when something's in capital P production,

00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:31.580
it means it is so vital to the health of your organization,

00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:34.059
to the correct operation of your organization,

00:01:34.059 --> 00:01:36.260
that if it stops working, someone

00:01:36.260 --> 00:01:39.180
is going to tell you, regardless of whether that's 3 PM

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:44.139
on a Monday afternoon or 3 AM on a Sunday morning.

00:01:44.139 --> 00:01:48.699
That's what capital P production means,

00:01:48.699 --> 00:01:53.180
that your code is vital to the health of your organization.

00:01:53.180 --> 00:02:00.339
And so I think you certainly can put R in production.

00:02:00.339 --> 00:02:03.379
But you probably don't want to, not because there's

00:02:03.379 --> 00:02:05.059
anything wrong with R, but because you

00:02:05.059 --> 00:02:08.820
don't want to put data scientists in production.

00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:14.259
Because your data scientists don't

00:02:14.259 --> 00:02:16.979
want to be woken up at 3 AM on a Sunday morning, right?

00:02:16.979 --> 00:02:19.699
That's not part of their job description.

00:02:19.699 --> 00:02:23.300
So it's totally fine to put data scientists in lowercase P

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:24.259
production.

00:02:24.259 --> 00:02:26.500
In fact, really important, because they're still

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:28.339
going to be your data scientists are

00:02:28.339 --> 00:02:30.179
going to be producing things that are really

00:02:30.179 --> 00:02:31.380
useful for your organization.

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:33.139
They're not so vital that someone has

00:02:33.139 --> 00:02:34.899
to be woken up if they break.

00:02:34.899 --> 00:02:36.740
But they're producing dashboards that people

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:38.740
are going to be looking at every day, every week.

00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:40.500
It's really important.

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:44.500
And you absolutely can put R into lowercase P production,

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:47.619
because the dirty secret of most organizations

00:02:47.619 --> 00:02:50.940
is they already have Excel in production.

00:02:50.940 --> 00:02:53.380
Like the number of organizations where

00:02:53.380 --> 00:02:57.899
there is some semi-automated Excel spreadsheet that

00:02:57.899 --> 00:03:00.139
is really, really important to someone

00:03:00.139 --> 00:03:05.300
in the executive part of the company is pretty high.

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:06.820
So with that said, what does it mean

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:09.660
to put something in lowercase P production?

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:13.100
Well, I'm not 100% sure, but I can tell you what it's not.

00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:15.860
First of all, something in production

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:17.899
isn't run just once.

00:03:17.899 --> 00:03:20.899
If you have a successful data analysis,

00:03:20.899 --> 00:03:23.860
it's going to need to be run again, and again, and again,

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:26.660
and again.

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:30.779
It's also not going to be just run on your computer.

00:03:30.779 --> 00:03:33.979
It's typically going to need to be deployed somewhere else,

00:03:33.979 --> 00:03:36.460
like deployed in production.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:38.779
That means it's typically going to be running on a server

00:03:38.779 --> 00:03:41.699
somewhere, not on your laptop.

00:03:41.699 --> 00:03:45.779
And then finally, if something's in production,

00:03:45.779 --> 00:03:47.699
it's no longer of importance to just you.

00:03:47.699 --> 00:03:49.699
You're not just the only person involved in it.

00:03:49.699 --> 00:03:53.580
You've got folks upstream, like data engineers.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:03:56.460
You've got your data scientist colleagues

00:03:56.460 --> 00:03:58.139
who you need to be able to collaborate with.

00:03:58.139 --> 00:04:02.139
And you have folks downstream, like the decision

00:04:02.139 --> 00:04:04.179
makers in your organization, or maybe

00:04:04.179 --> 00:04:06.020
other developers in your organization

00:04:06.020 --> 00:04:08.220
who want to be able to use the results of your models

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:10.940
through a traditional API.

00:04:11.059 --> 00:04:14.100
Now today, I'm going to focus on these two.

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:17.540
So what are the challenges that arise

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:20.260
when your R code is no longer running just

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:23.779
once on your computer?

00:04:23.779 --> 00:04:25.820
And so what I want you to do is to imagine

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:32.459
that you're a data scientist who works for an ice CM company.

00:04:32.459 --> 00:04:35.700
And what you want to do is predict.

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:37.820
You want to help your business by predicting

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:40.260
the sales of ice cream tomorrow, maybe

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:43.660
based on the sales of ice cream today, the temperature today,

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:45.940
and the forecast for tomorrow.

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:47.660
So you collect a bunch of data.

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:49.420
You write a bunch of code.

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:50.980
You fit some models.

00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:55.579
And then you come up with a beautiful dashboard.

00:04:55.579 --> 00:04:57.220
And this is great.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:04:59.779
You know, you've taken into account important variables

00:04:59.779 --> 00:05:06.500
like humidity, and Simba sup, and Chima,

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:08.940
and made in holidays, made something

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:11.220
that's really useful for your organization

00:05:11.220 --> 00:05:13.619
to make better decisions.

00:05:13.619 --> 00:05:15.579
But now you've got to take that dashboard,

00:05:15.579 --> 00:05:18.380
and it needs to work like every day.

00:05:18.380 --> 00:05:20.940
You need to kind of productionalize this

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:25.619
so that ideally, your code stays the same.

00:05:25.619 --> 00:05:31.660
You get some new data, and it produces the correct dashboard.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:33.220
And now of course, going into this,

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:35.380
like you know the data is going to change, right?

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:37.339
Because obviously, the ice cream size

00:05:37.339 --> 00:05:42.299
cram sales are going to drop in winter.

00:05:42.299 --> 00:05:45.899
But a big risk is that the schema of the data

00:05:45.899 --> 00:05:48.059
might change.

00:05:48.059 --> 00:05:51.540
So imagine, you know, obviously you are probably not out there

00:05:51.540 --> 00:05:53.140
recording the temperature each day.

00:05:53.140 --> 00:05:55.779
You're using some API to get weather data.

00:05:55.779 --> 00:05:57.500
And so far, you've been working with it.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:01.420
You've got the dates in month, day, year format,

00:06:01.420 --> 00:06:03.339
and the temperature.

00:06:03.339 --> 00:06:05.859
And you know, your API changes.

00:06:05.899 --> 00:06:07.700
It's now going to give you the data

00:06:07.700 --> 00:06:10.980
in a slightly different format.

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:12.899
So I'm going to give you all a quick challenge.

00:06:12.899 --> 00:06:15.299
What I want you to do is compare the old data on the left

00:06:15.299 --> 00:06:16.459
to the new data on the right.

00:06:16.459 --> 00:06:19.540
Like, can you figure out what's different, what's changed?

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:24.100
And how is this likely to impact your analysis?

00:06:24.100 --> 00:06:28.220
So let's take a minute or two, turn to your neighbor,

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:30.260
see if you can figure out what's different,

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:32.660
and how is it going to impact your analysis.

00:06:36.019 --> 00:06:37.500
How are we doing?

00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:38.500
Why are we out here?

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:40.859
Well, this actually takes more practice camping

00:06:40.859 --> 00:06:42.339
than structured, right?

00:06:42.339 --> 00:06:44.579
Because what we're doing here is sending data

00:06:44.579 --> 00:06:45.540
in each direction.

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:47.140
We're calculating the behavior of the data that's

00:06:47.140 --> 00:06:48.339
currently connected to that.

00:06:48.339 --> 00:06:49.619
And what we want is this.

00:06:49.619 --> 00:06:51.380
We're recommending we're finding our own way

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:53.480
to change grand maps, to change the maps

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:55.779
that somebodyraw the map, that we use with Red and Orange,

00:06:55.779 --> 00:06:57.779
that we're pushing border to border.

00:06:57.779 --> 00:06:59.859
And our data needs a connection to voltage

00:06:59.859 --> 00:07:01.100
that will tell us the exact time.

00:07:01.100 --> 00:07:02.980
Well, let me give you a quick example.

00:07:02.980 --> 00:07:05.559
So we might have a bunch of classes in the class,

00:07:05.959 --> 00:07:21.160
OK, time's up.

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:23.339
Who wants to yell out one difference they spotted?

00:07:23.339 --> 00:07:27.359
The column names, right?

00:07:27.359 --> 00:07:29.839
We've changed temperature to temp.

00:07:29.839 --> 00:07:34.119
So what impact is this likely to have on your analysis?

00:07:34.119 --> 00:07:36.040
It's probably going to break, right?

00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:39.079
It's probably going to break actually in quite a good way

00:07:39.079 --> 00:07:40.440
because it's going to say, oh, you

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:44.279
don't have a variable called temperature anymore.

00:07:44.279 --> 00:07:47.200
What else has changed?

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:49.320
The date format, right?

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:53.359
We've gone from American style to ISO 8601,

00:07:53.359 --> 00:07:55.320
the only true way of recording dates.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:00.519
So what impact do you think this is

00:08:00.519 --> 00:08:01.859
going to have on your analysis?

00:08:05.119 --> 00:08:07.040
Like, you might be lucky, right?

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:08.959
Maybe when you read this data in,

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:11.839
you're just relying on whatever library, whatever

00:08:11.839 --> 00:08:13.760
package you're using to read this to automatically

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:15.399
recognize this as a date.

00:08:15.399 --> 00:08:16.480
So this is still a date.

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:18.519
So it might just work.

00:08:18.519 --> 00:08:21.160
Or if you've explicitly specified

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:24.480
that this is month, day, year, this is going to cause an error.

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:28.839
Again, probably quite a clear error.

00:08:28.839 --> 00:08:30.000
What about the last change?

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:34.640
I'm guessing it's probably gone from Fahrenheit to Celsius.

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:39.280
And what impact is this going to have on your analysis?

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:42.039
Your model's just going to give nonsense results, right?

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:44.719
This is the worst case scenario because you're not

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:45.760
going to get an error.

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:48.799
It's just going to silently start returning garbage.

00:08:48.799 --> 00:08:50.520
And so I think this sort of change,

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:53.799
like when I talk to folks who are actually

00:08:53.799 --> 00:08:57.119
doing data science, this sort of change

00:08:57.799 --> 00:09:02.200
is, I think, the most painful thing that people face today.

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:05.919
So how can we de-risk that?

00:09:05.919 --> 00:09:08.719
Well, the first piece of advice probably no one

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:09.919
is really going to appreciate.

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:13.320
But my first piece of advice is you need to make friends.

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:15.320
You need to make friends with the people who

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:18.119
are producing your data so that they at least

00:09:18.119 --> 00:09:20.119
know you're relying on it and give you a heads

00:09:20.119 --> 00:09:21.760
up when something changes.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.559
There's a really big kind of people component

00:09:25.159 --> 00:09:27.760
to this, that you have to be talking to those people.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:29.640
You have to be collaborating with them.

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:31.799
And if you're not, like technology,

00:09:31.799 --> 00:09:35.239
you can certainly prevent the worst of foot guns,

00:09:35.239 --> 00:09:36.520
but it's not the real solution.

00:09:36.520 --> 00:09:38.119
It's going to alert you to a problem,

00:09:38.119 --> 00:09:41.719
but it's not going to help you solve it.

00:09:41.719 --> 00:09:45.559
Technologically, what you can do is use a package like point

00:09:45.559 --> 00:09:49.520
blank or great expectations to define the schema that you

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:52.159
expect for your data.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:55.599
How many of you have used point blank before?

00:09:55.599 --> 00:09:58.400
How many of you have used great expectations?

00:09:58.400 --> 00:09:59.599
OK, a few of these.

00:09:59.599 --> 00:10:01.599
Really useful tools because they allow

00:10:01.599 --> 00:10:05.200
you to make precise exactly what you expect the data to look

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:06.200
like.

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:09.760
And then if the data changes, you're going to get an error.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:11.359
Like this doesn't solve the problem,

00:10:11.359 --> 00:10:13.239
right, but it ensures that you're not just,

00:10:13.239 --> 00:10:16.239
your analysis isn't just going to give silently nonsense

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:18.559
results.

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:20.359
You're still going to have to make friends.

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:22.640
You're still going to have to make friends

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:26.880
with whoever changed the data and figure out what happened.

00:10:26.880 --> 00:10:31.320
But at least you know there's a problem.

00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:33.159
OK, so what else can go wrong?

00:10:33.159 --> 00:10:35.159
Well, maybe a dependency changes.

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:45.960
It's really like a, you're not updating.

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:48.760
OK, now it's updated.

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:51.640
OK, having like it's somewhere variable lag

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:53.960
in five seconds and 30 seconds.

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:55.039
It's really fun.

00:10:55.039 --> 00:10:56.479
So a dependency might change.

00:10:56.479 --> 00:10:59.919
So you have a new version of your favorite package

00:10:59.919 --> 00:11:02.320
comes out with amazing new features,

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:06.200
but it breaks your code in some way, which

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:09.280
is like really frustrating, right?

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:10.479
So how do you de-risk this?

00:11:10.479 --> 00:11:13.320
I think there's some pretty good tools available.

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:18.799
I think this is basically a solved problem for reasons

00:11:18.799 --> 00:11:19.919
I'll talk about shortly.

00:11:19.919 --> 00:11:21.280
But the way you solve this problem

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:23.280
is by using a virtual environment.

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:24.799
And what a virtual environment does

00:11:24.799 --> 00:11:27.760
is just captures for this project, what

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:31.520
are the versions of R packages or Python packages

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:32.400
that you're using.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.799
So you no longer are using the latest version of everything

00:11:35.799 --> 00:11:37.440
or whatever collection of packages

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:39.679
happens to be installed on your computer or whatever.

00:11:39.679 --> 00:11:41.159
You're using a virtual environment.

00:11:41.159 --> 00:11:43.320
Packages happens to be installed on your computer

00:11:43.320 --> 00:11:44.200
at this time.

00:11:44.200 --> 00:11:49.320
You're using a specific known set of packages.

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:51.640
And you need to do this anyway when

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:54.159
we get into this not just on my computer problem,

00:11:54.159 --> 00:11:56.559
because if you're going to run this code somewhere else,

00:11:56.559 --> 00:11:58.679
you also need to capture those dependencies

00:11:58.679 --> 00:12:00.760
and ship them somewhere else.

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:03.919
And so the reason I think this is basically a solved problem

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:07.679
is that if you use PositConnect, that when you deploy something

00:12:07.679 --> 00:12:09.320
to PositConnect, it automatically

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:10.960
creates a virtual environment for you.

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:14.359
It automatically captures, even if you're not already

00:12:14.359 --> 00:12:16.039
using one, it's going to capture what

00:12:16.039 --> 00:12:19.640
are the exact version of all of your dependencies.

00:12:19.640 --> 00:12:23.000
And then every time your report is rerun on Connect,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:24.679
it's going to use exactly the same version

00:12:24.679 --> 00:12:26.239
of those dependencies.

00:12:26.239 --> 00:12:27.960
And that seems to have, by and large,

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:29.479
fixed this problem for most people.

00:12:29.479 --> 00:12:35.280
This is not what's causing pain for most data scientists.

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:37.159
Now, there's kind of another related problem.

00:12:37.159 --> 00:12:38.960
And it's not just the dependencies,

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:41.599
like the R and Python packages you're using,

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:45.080
but it's that entire stack of all the computations

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:48.640
that eventually lead up to some electrons moving around

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:49.640
on a chip.

00:12:49.640 --> 00:12:53.840
So maybe Apple has come out with an amazing new laptop

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:55.479
with a new chip on it.

00:12:55.479 --> 00:12:59.359
Maybe that's going to cause some of your results to change.

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:02.239
Or maybe there is just a new version of the operating

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:03.320
system.

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:05.359
And something about the way that it does,

00:13:05.359 --> 00:13:10.000
it optimizes metric algebra, means

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.039
that you get some slightly different numbers.

00:13:12.039 --> 00:13:15.559
Or something in your other dependency stack,

00:13:15.559 --> 00:13:17.400
one of your system library changes,

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:20.840
or maybe R or Python versions change themselves.

00:13:20.840 --> 00:13:24.320
So this, I think, can occasionally be a problem.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:26.479
It's pretty rare these days, because we

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:28.440
have a good solution for this, which

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:32.479
is like running containers on commodity hardware.

00:13:32.479 --> 00:13:33.880
So a virtual environment is going

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:37.479
to capture your R and Python package dependencies.

00:13:37.479 --> 00:13:39.559
A container kind of captures everything else.

00:13:39.559 --> 00:13:41.520
The version of the operating system,

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:44.799
the versions of like BLAST, which

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:48.280
is powering your linear algebra computations,

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:50.039
that captures everything else.

00:13:50.039 --> 00:13:52.520
So capturing the dependencies, I think

00:13:52.520 --> 00:13:56.679
that solves like, I don't know, 95% of these problems.

00:13:56.679 --> 00:13:59.760
Capturing everything else that a container captures

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:02.960
solves like another 4% or 4.9%.

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:05.159
And then you've just got a very weird long tail

00:14:05.159 --> 00:14:06.039
of other problems.

00:14:06.039 --> 00:14:08.039
But again, mostly a solved problem.

00:14:11.719 --> 00:14:16.239
A much bigger challenge is that the universe is also

00:14:16.239 --> 00:14:17.760
going to change.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:19.200
So there might be a big change.

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:21.599
Maybe your ice cream shop has moved to a new location

00:14:21.599 --> 00:14:22.799
on the beach.

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:25.200
That's obviously going to have profound impact

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:29.559
on how many ice creams people are buying.

00:14:29.559 --> 00:14:32.760
But even when there isn't a profound change,

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:36.799
every model isn't necessarily a simplification of the universe.

00:14:36.799 --> 00:14:39.559
It's kind of a Taylor series approximation.

00:14:39.559 --> 00:14:42.280
And as you move further and further away

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:44.840
from that approximation point in time,

00:14:44.840 --> 00:14:47.919
that approximation is probably going to get worse and worse.

00:14:47.919 --> 00:14:50.119
Maybe not by a huge amount, but it's going to slowly

00:14:50.119 --> 00:14:53.440
get poorer and poorer.

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:55.719
So you might have heard terms like concept drift,

00:14:55.719 --> 00:14:57.599
or model drift, or data drift.

00:14:57.599 --> 00:14:59.679
I think these are all ideas that are reflecting

00:14:59.679 --> 00:15:02.080
that the universe is changing.

00:15:02.080 --> 00:15:04.640
It doesn't matter how good your model is today,

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:07.559
if you're not regularly refitting it

00:15:07.559 --> 00:15:09.159
with new training data.

00:15:09.159 --> 00:15:10.840
And then occasionally, even thinking

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:13.440
about the whole functional form of the model,

00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:16.039
thinking about rebuilding the model from scratch,

00:15:16.039 --> 00:15:20.640
it's just going to gradually drift into irrelevance.

00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:22.960
So how do you de-risk this?

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:25.520
I think the way you de-risk this is by just,

00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:27.000
you have to acknowledge it.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.039
A model is not a sit and forget type thing.

00:15:30.039 --> 00:15:32.840
You're going to have to monitor it over time.

00:15:32.840 --> 00:15:34.320
You're going to have to regularly,

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:37.320
as well as the dashboard that maybe

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:39.000
uses the predictions from the models

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.520
to show to the decision makers in your organization,

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:44.000
you also need a dashboard for you

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.320
to look at as a data scientist that tells you information

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:51.000
about the model metrics.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:52.520
So there's tons of tools for this.

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:54.400
I know about two of them, because they're

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:56.760
produced by my colleagues at Posit.

00:15:56.760 --> 00:15:59.840
The first one is Vediva, a toolkit for R and Python

00:16:00.640 --> 00:16:03.679
that makes it really easy to create this model monitoring

00:16:03.679 --> 00:16:07.799
system, those regularly updated reports

00:16:07.799 --> 00:16:10.280
about the quality of your model.

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:12.919
How many people have heard of Vediva before?

00:16:12.919 --> 00:16:13.799
OK, cool.

00:16:13.799 --> 00:16:16.320
And another really interesting package is called Applicable.

00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:18.039
How many of you have heard of Applicable?

00:16:18.039 --> 00:16:19.119
For a few of you.

00:16:19.119 --> 00:16:21.479
So the idea of Applicable is it's

00:16:21.479 --> 00:16:27.799
going to try and help you detect if the data you're

00:16:27.799 --> 00:16:30.520
using to make predictions with has

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:33.640
drifted a long way from the data that you

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:36.359
were used to fit the model.

00:16:36.359 --> 00:16:39.400
So have you moved from an area of confidence

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:41.520
where you've got tons of data to an area

00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:46.479
where now you're extrapolating the model from afar?

00:16:46.479 --> 00:16:48.119
And I think this is really important.

00:16:48.119 --> 00:16:50.280
This seems to me like something that you want.

00:16:50.280 --> 00:16:52.520
Every time you do a prediction, you really

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:56.599
want to know, do I think this is a good prediction?

00:16:56.599 --> 00:17:00.080
And a model can't kind of reach outside of itself

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:02.479
and say, oh, this is not in the model.

00:17:02.479 --> 00:17:07.760
This is kind of one of the big problems with LLMs right now.

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:09.319
They very rarely say, I don't know.

00:17:09.319 --> 00:17:10.800
They just make something up.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:13.000
That's a characteristic of every model.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.839
But you can use tools like Applicable to at least say,

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:18.239
well, the data point I'm making a prediction about

00:17:18.239 --> 00:17:21.640
is a long way from the data that I used to fit this model.

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:26.479
And I probably need to be pretty skeptical about that.

00:17:26.479 --> 00:17:27.959
And I've talked about models here.

00:17:27.959 --> 00:17:29.640
But the same thing applies if you're

00:17:29.640 --> 00:17:32.319
creating a dashboard or a visualization, right?

00:17:32.319 --> 00:17:33.800
You've created a visualization.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:36.680
You've created a dashboard that presumably you're

00:17:36.680 --> 00:17:40.239
going to show the most important things.

00:17:40.239 --> 00:17:43.199
And those most important things are probably

00:17:43.199 --> 00:17:45.959
going to change over time.

00:17:45.959 --> 00:17:48.599
And I think this is something that really surprised me

00:17:48.599 --> 00:17:52.680
when I learned about how people use dashboards in real life,

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:54.719
is that if a dashboard is successful,

00:17:54.719 --> 00:17:56.560
it's typically not static.

00:17:56.560 --> 00:17:58.439
It's going to change over time.

00:17:58.439 --> 00:18:03.160
And part of this is almost inherent

00:18:03.160 --> 00:18:05.880
in the nature of a good visualization

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:07.400
or a good dashboard, right?

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:10.520
If it's successful, people are going

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:13.119
to make decisions based on it that

00:18:13.119 --> 00:18:16.599
were different to what they would have made without it.

00:18:16.599 --> 00:18:18.400
And so now you've kind of violated

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:22.640
this fundamental idea that the time after the dashboard

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:24.640
is different to the time before the dashboard,

00:18:24.640 --> 00:18:26.640
because people are making different decisions.

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:28.160
And that's probably going to affect

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:30.880
how your model sees the world.

00:18:33.640 --> 00:18:38.959
And the last and kind of most kind of mixed problem

00:18:38.959 --> 00:18:40.560
is that the requirements change.

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:42.280
In some ways, the worst thing that

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:44.160
could happen to your dashboard is

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:49.000
it becomes so successful that your fat cat CEO is now

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:50.800
looking at it every day.

00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:56.719
And they have a constant stream of comments and feedback

00:18:56.719 --> 00:19:00.880
and changes that they want made to that dashboard.

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:04.680
And I think this is challenging not just because you've

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:08.000
got to make changes, but I think that's something that few,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.680
it's not something you learn as a data scientist

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:12.280
in your college courses.

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:15.119
How do you respond to people asking you

00:19:15.119 --> 00:19:17.880
to make all of these changes?

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:20.040
Just the way you think about the problem,

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:24.479
the way you respond to people asking you for help,

00:19:24.479 --> 00:19:26.959
particularly people above you in the organization,

00:19:26.959 --> 00:19:28.880
how do you make sure that you can still

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:31.719
do your actual job while responding

00:19:31.719 --> 00:19:33.680
to the stream of minor changes from people

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:37.319
higher up in the org chart to you?

00:19:37.319 --> 00:19:39.520
But I think there's also, I don't know,

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:40.439
there's something else.

00:19:40.439 --> 00:19:42.319
I don't really know how you de-risk this.

00:19:42.319 --> 00:19:46.880
I think one big part of it is this idea of refactoring,

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:50.640
that it's really important to spend some time working

00:19:50.640 --> 00:19:55.959
with your code, not to add new features, not to fix bugs,

00:19:55.959 --> 00:19:58.359
but to make that code easier to maintain.

00:19:58.359 --> 00:20:01.239
And that's the true idea of refactoring,

00:20:01.239 --> 00:20:05.640
is to spend time improving the quality of your code

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:09.079
so that it's easier to change in the future.

00:20:09.079 --> 00:20:11.599
You have to recognize and embrace the fact

00:20:11.599 --> 00:20:13.199
that everything you do is going to have

00:20:13.199 --> 00:20:14.880
to change in the future.

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:16.800
And ideally, you want your velocity

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:19.359
to increase over time as you get a better

00:20:19.359 --> 00:20:20.959
understanding of the domain.

00:20:20.959 --> 00:20:22.920
As you become a better programmer,

00:20:22.920 --> 00:20:25.839
you want to get faster at making these changes.

00:20:25.839 --> 00:20:31.479
You don't want to get slower as this massive backlog of things

00:20:31.479 --> 00:20:33.319
start to drag you down.

00:20:33.319 --> 00:20:35.760
And every time you go back to an old project,

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:38.880
you just feel awful because you don't really

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:40.319
understand how it works.

00:20:40.319 --> 00:20:42.599
And you're worried about any change you make

00:20:42.599 --> 00:20:46.000
is going to make the problem that much worse.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.239
And I think software engineers learn more,

00:20:49.239 --> 00:20:51.640
or at least software engineering managers,

00:20:51.640 --> 00:20:55.160
understand a bit more how important this is,

00:20:55.160 --> 00:20:58.520
making changes for the sake of future change.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:00.439
But I don't think that's necessarily something

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:02.719
like data scientists and data science managers

00:21:02.719 --> 00:21:04.800
know how to talk about and to justify.

00:21:08.079 --> 00:21:10.800
So these are the five things that I

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:14.400
think are the biggest challenges when

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:16.959
you have an analysis that's successful enough

00:21:16.959 --> 00:21:19.599
that you do it again and again and again and again.

00:21:19.599 --> 00:21:23.079
The schema changing, I think, from my conversations

00:21:23.079 --> 00:21:25.400
with people doing data science out in the world,

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:28.680
this is the number one pain point right now.

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:30.560
Dependencies and platform changes,

00:21:30.560 --> 00:21:32.079
sure, they're kind of annoying.

00:21:32.079 --> 00:21:34.839
But we've got good technology to mostly make

00:21:34.839 --> 00:21:37.400
those problems go away.

00:21:37.400 --> 00:21:40.719
Universe changing, I think most people,

00:21:40.719 --> 00:21:43.280
the way they solve that is by just closing their eyes.

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:46.359
And the way that people handle requirements changing

00:21:46.359 --> 00:21:48.319
is covering their ears.

00:21:48.319 --> 00:21:51.400
But I think really important.

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:53.479
Again, like this is, I don't really know.

00:21:53.479 --> 00:21:57.959
I've never put code into production, really.

00:21:57.959 --> 00:21:59.199
Well, I guess I did have.

00:21:59.199 --> 00:22:02.319
I'll tell you the one thing that was closest to production

00:22:02.319 --> 00:22:06.000
is that there was an artist that I really liked.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:07.359
He was like on TikTok.

00:22:07.359 --> 00:22:10.760
So anytime he posted anything on his website, it would go out.

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:12.959
It would be sold in like 15 minutes.

00:22:12.959 --> 00:22:15.000
So what I did is I wrote an R script

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.280
that ran every 15 minutes on GitHub Actions

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:19.599
and scraped his website and then was

00:22:19.599 --> 00:22:22.280
supposed to text me when anything changed

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:25.160
so I could quickly go and buy it.

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:29.239
And I never managed to get that to successfully work.

00:22:29.239 --> 00:22:31.359
Like it did actually scrape and collect some data,

00:22:31.359 --> 00:22:33.920
but I could never actually get it to send me information

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:35.719
to make a decision.

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:38.199
But because I was like checking on it so often,

00:22:38.199 --> 00:22:40.359
I noticed that when the site updated

00:22:40.359 --> 00:22:42.680
and managed to buy some R.

00:22:42.680 --> 00:22:44.280
So again, I'm no expert in this.

00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:46.880
So I'd love you to just take a minute or two,

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:48.119
talk it over with your neighbor.

00:22:48.119 --> 00:22:49.719
Like are there problems that you've

00:22:49.719 --> 00:22:51.599
faced putting R in production that you don't

00:22:51.599 --> 00:22:52.959
think I've captured here?

00:22:52.959 --> 00:22:56.400
So take a minute or two and then you can yell out a few things

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:02.760
or you can email me or LinkedIn me, I guess.

00:23:02.760 --> 00:23:03.599
So take a minute.

00:23:03.599 --> 00:23:04.400
Talk it over.

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:05.199
What have I missed?

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:36.599
Time's up.

00:24:36.599 --> 00:24:39.520
Anyone want to yell out any ideas?

00:24:39.520 --> 00:24:41.920
Mark?

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:44.800
So one thing that I think you need to address here

00:24:44.800 --> 00:24:48.760
is also the code itself, which you're not

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:50.520
explicitly talking about.

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:53.479
I actually gave a talk about this at GCR last year.

00:24:53.479 --> 00:24:57.599
So your code needs to be able to run on a pendant, number one.

00:24:57.599 --> 00:25:00.599
Because it's going to be run on a machine on the system

00:25:00.599 --> 00:25:03.719
and it should not expect any sort of user input.

00:25:03.719 --> 00:25:05.640
Or if it does, number one.

00:25:05.640 --> 00:25:07.319
Number two, parametrization.

00:25:07.319 --> 00:25:07.819
Yep.

00:25:07.819 --> 00:25:10.479
Right, you're putting some parametrized three-hour

00:25:10.479 --> 00:25:13.640
logging so that it doesn't debug.

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:15.719
We're actually going to cover most of those points

00:25:15.719 --> 00:25:16.959
in the next part of the talk.

00:25:21.079 --> 00:25:22.599
Cool, thanks.

00:25:22.599 --> 00:25:23.719
Anything else?

00:25:23.719 --> 00:25:24.219
Yeah.

00:25:24.219 --> 00:25:26.359
When a solution to the scale problem

00:25:26.359 --> 00:25:28.239
is addressed, it's contracts often

00:25:28.239 --> 00:25:30.800
held up to a solution that's already

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:32.800
available because they're using the system away

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:34.560
instead of using a different handler

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:36.040
connecting directly to their database

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:39.040
and asking them to build a new API instead.

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:41.560
And then that's what you're expected to hold to

00:25:41.560 --> 00:25:43.040
is more of a pressure.

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:46.560
So do you think of contracts as more of a people thing

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:48.959
or a technology thing?

00:25:48.959 --> 00:25:49.680
Or a mix?

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:52.160
It's an agreement among people for how technology is used.

00:25:52.160 --> 00:25:53.920
Yeah.

00:25:53.920 --> 00:25:54.420
Cool.

00:25:54.420 --> 00:25:55.800
Anything else?

00:25:55.800 --> 00:25:57.319
Yeah.

00:25:57.319 --> 00:25:59.079
Your team changes.

00:25:59.079 --> 00:26:03.040
Can you leave and add some institutional knowledge

00:26:03.040 --> 00:26:04.400
of this project?

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:05.640
Yeah, that's a really good one.

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:09.800
That's sort of covered in the not just one person

00:26:09.800 --> 00:26:13.719
doing any more, which I'm not going to talk about.

00:26:13.719 --> 00:26:15.839
Maybe if you remind me at the end and we have time,

00:26:15.839 --> 00:26:21.760
I'll show you one picture that I have made, not AI.

00:26:21.760 --> 00:26:23.599
So those are kind of the problems related

00:26:23.599 --> 00:26:26.239
to running your code repeatedly.

00:26:26.239 --> 00:26:28.599
Now I want to talk about the problems more

00:26:28.599 --> 00:26:32.319
related to running your code somewhere else.

00:26:32.319 --> 00:26:34.599
And these problems aren't independent,

00:26:34.599 --> 00:26:36.920
but I think this character, this sort of breakdown

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:38.839
is still useful.

00:26:38.839 --> 00:26:41.640
Because I think there are sort of three possible ways

00:26:41.640 --> 00:26:42.719
your code might be running.

00:26:42.719 --> 00:26:45.800
And not every organization has all three of these,

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:49.599
but I think many organizations do.

00:26:49.599 --> 00:26:53.239
Like you might be running code on your laptop, right?

00:26:53.239 --> 00:26:56.119
This is just kind of like the wild west of data science.

00:26:56.119 --> 00:26:58.680
And depending on your organization,

00:26:58.680 --> 00:27:00.680
you might be able to do whatever the hell you want

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:03.640
on your laptop.

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:08.119
You might also have some kind of central compute service.

00:27:08.119 --> 00:27:09.680
So maybe that's some instance that's

00:27:09.680 --> 00:27:12.959
running on shared hardware that's fast

00:27:12.959 --> 00:27:15.599
or on some kind of container setup

00:27:15.599 --> 00:27:17.760
that's all centrally managed so everyone's using

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:20.119
the same versions of things.

00:27:20.119 --> 00:27:21.800
And then you're often going to have,

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:24.479
or hopefully you have, some kind of like combination

00:27:24.520 --> 00:27:27.439
of staging and deployment environment.

00:27:27.439 --> 00:27:30.880
So these tend to be like run unattended.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:33.760
And you really want two of these things.

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:36.479
They're basically identical, but I think the main difference

00:27:36.479 --> 00:27:38.400
is like your staging environment,

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:40.760
like data scientists look at that.

00:27:40.760 --> 00:27:43.319
And decision makers look at the deployment environment.

00:27:43.319 --> 00:27:46.199
They're otherwise identical, but it means you can like

00:27:46.199 --> 00:27:48.479
put something, send something to staging

00:27:48.479 --> 00:27:50.760
and look at it to see if it's working or not

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:52.680
without accidentally breaking the things

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:54.439
that the people in your organization

00:27:54.439 --> 00:27:57.319
use to make decisions.

00:27:57.319 --> 00:27:58.959
And I think these, I've kind of put,

00:27:58.959 --> 00:28:01.280
they're pretty thick lines here because there's

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:06.839
some fairly big challenges in each of these transitions.

00:28:06.839 --> 00:28:09.640
You know, kind of one of the things that,

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:11.560
I think like one of the goals of Posit,

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:17.199
the company that I work for, is to help with each of these.

00:28:17.199 --> 00:28:20.160
And when the slide updates, this is kind of

00:28:20.160 --> 00:28:21.839
correspond to our like different products.

00:28:21.839 --> 00:28:23.520
Like the idea of Posit Workbench,

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:25.079
that helps you run something like,

00:28:25.079 --> 00:28:28.719
like run the RStudio IDE, Jupyter Notebooks,

00:28:28.719 --> 00:28:31.280
Visual Code, like in a standardized way

00:28:31.280 --> 00:28:35.160
that's centrally maintained pretty easily.

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:39.599
RStudio Connect allows you to deploy things like apps,

00:28:39.599 --> 00:28:41.959
Shiny apps, like Markdown documents,

00:28:41.959 --> 00:28:45.119
Cordo documents, Dash apps, Flask apps,

00:28:45.119 --> 00:28:48.479
in a way where you can kind of work on your laptop

00:28:48.479 --> 00:28:51.040
or central compute and just get things published

00:28:51.040 --> 00:28:52.160
as easily as possible.

00:28:55.239 --> 00:28:56.520
OK, now it updated.

00:28:56.520 --> 00:28:58.719
OK, and so what I want to talk a little bit about

00:28:58.719 --> 00:29:01.599
is like how do we cross these various chasms?

00:29:01.599 --> 00:29:04.160
And I think just the first thing is just to be aware of them.

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:05.800
Right, at each of these points, there's

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:08.079
some pain associated with it.

00:29:08.079 --> 00:29:14.880
And particularly like if you are a Windows user, like Jared,

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:16.319
there's going to be some pain.

00:29:16.319 --> 00:29:17.959
Because now when you deploy, when you're

00:29:17.959 --> 00:29:19.560
using a central compute or deployment,

00:29:19.560 --> 00:29:22.520
it's almost certainly going to be in Linux.

00:29:22.520 --> 00:29:25.119
There's also some differences just between desktop machines

00:29:25.119 --> 00:29:28.119
and servers generally.

00:29:28.119 --> 00:29:29.920
Then as Mark pointed out, there's

00:29:29.920 --> 00:29:32.599
some major pain points moving from an environment where

00:29:32.599 --> 00:29:35.719
you can debug interactively to an environment where

00:29:35.719 --> 00:29:37.079
you run a script.

00:29:37.079 --> 00:29:41.839
And 30 minutes later, you get an error message back.

00:29:41.839 --> 00:29:43.959
And there's also some similar challenges

00:29:43.959 --> 00:29:47.479
that arise related to like who is doing the analysis.

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:50.920
Like typically, on your laptop or in central compute,

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:53.959
like the person doing the analysis is you.

00:29:53.959 --> 00:29:57.239
It's your access to the database that chooses

00:29:57.239 --> 00:29:58.839
what data to come back.

00:29:58.839 --> 00:30:01.199
When you start moving into a staging environment

00:30:01.199 --> 00:30:02.959
or a deployment environment, you need

00:30:02.959 --> 00:30:08.199
to think about like whose access is being used to get the data.

00:30:08.199 --> 00:30:09.680
This is like particularly important

00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:10.880
when the data is sensitive.

00:30:10.880 --> 00:30:12.560
And like different people in your organization

00:30:12.560 --> 00:30:14.260
can see different views of the data set.

00:30:14.959 --> 00:30:15.459
OK.

00:30:15.459 --> 00:30:17.060
So the first challenge to overcome

00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:19.060
is if you're a Windows user on your laptop,

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:20.660
there's a bunch of things that are just

00:30:20.660 --> 00:30:23.979
different on Linux for like historic reasons.

00:30:23.979 --> 00:30:25.619
None of them are particularly important,

00:30:25.619 --> 00:30:27.939
but they're all annoying and they will all catch you out.

00:30:27.939 --> 00:30:29.900
Like Windows uses different line endings.

00:30:29.900 --> 00:30:31.900
It uses a different character encoding in R,

00:30:31.900 --> 00:30:34.099
and it uses a different path separator.

00:30:34.099 --> 00:30:36.099
And all of these are just like little things

00:30:36.099 --> 00:30:40.140
you will stub your toe on again and again and again and again.

00:30:40.140 --> 00:30:42.540
And I guess I stub my toe on these things

00:30:42.540 --> 00:30:45.819
I stub my toe on these things too because I generally

00:30:45.819 --> 00:30:48.619
write my code on a Mac, which for these purposes

00:30:48.619 --> 00:30:50.459
is functionally a Linux.

00:30:50.459 --> 00:30:52.859
And then when I test my code on Windows machines,

00:30:52.859 --> 00:30:54.780
I'm like, oh, the path separator is wrong.

00:30:54.780 --> 00:30:57.540
Oh, there's some weird thing in my test snapshots

00:30:57.540 --> 00:31:01.459
because the line endings are different.

00:31:01.459 --> 00:31:05.619
Also differences because your computer is a desktop

00:31:05.619 --> 00:31:08.219
and the central computer is a server.

00:31:08.219 --> 00:31:10.739
Like a desktop is set up for like you.

00:31:10.819 --> 00:31:13.099
It has set up to use your time zone.

00:31:13.099 --> 00:31:15.619
It's set up to use your language of preference.

00:31:15.619 --> 00:31:17.859
It has all of the fonts you've installed,

00:31:17.859 --> 00:31:21.260
and it has graphics devices that lots of people use

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:23.739
and a lot of care has been put into.

00:31:23.739 --> 00:31:24.859
When you move to a server,

00:31:24.859 --> 00:31:28.579
it's probably defaulting to a UTC time zone.

00:31:28.579 --> 00:31:32.660
So that's sort of basically the same as Greenwich Mean Time.

00:31:32.660 --> 00:31:35.180
It's probably using a C locale.

00:31:35.180 --> 00:31:40.060
So it just sorts things in kind of the ASCII order.

00:31:40.099 --> 00:31:42.020
Probably doesn't have many fonts installed,

00:31:42.020 --> 00:31:45.780
and it probably has kind of crappy graphics devices.

00:31:45.780 --> 00:31:47.260
The first two are gonna cause

00:31:47.260 --> 00:31:49.300
potentially problems for your code.

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:51.819
One of the things like we've tried to do in the tidyverse

00:31:51.819 --> 00:31:54.579
is make sure as much as possible

00:31:54.579 --> 00:31:57.020
you don't automatically derive those things.

00:31:57.859 --> 00:32:00.660
For example, there's a really interesting problem

00:32:00.660 --> 00:32:03.859
that in different, some different,

00:32:03.859 --> 00:32:06.219
some locales sort the letters of the alphabet

00:32:06.219 --> 00:32:09.939
differently to other locales.

00:32:10.819 --> 00:32:13.060
The order of a factor in R by default

00:32:13.060 --> 00:32:14.780
is alphabetical ordering,

00:32:14.780 --> 00:32:17.859
and that determines your contrast of a linear model.

00:32:17.859 --> 00:32:19.739
So it is possible, it's pretty unusual,

00:32:19.739 --> 00:32:21.900
but it's possible and it has happened to people

00:32:21.900 --> 00:32:24.619
that by running code in a different locale,

00:32:24.619 --> 00:32:26.739
you get a bunch of different contrasts

00:32:26.739 --> 00:32:27.939
outputted from your model.

00:32:27.939 --> 00:32:29.140
Like the model's still the same,

00:32:29.140 --> 00:32:31.979
but it's confusing for people looking at the outputs.

00:32:32.819 --> 00:32:34.339
And the last two are just pain points.

00:32:34.339 --> 00:32:35.459
Like if you're trying to make sure

00:32:35.459 --> 00:32:38.020
all of your plots look exactly the same

00:32:38.020 --> 00:32:39.579
using your corporate style guide,

00:32:39.579 --> 00:32:40.819
your approved fonts,

00:32:40.819 --> 00:32:42.339
this is just a pain to get right

00:32:42.339 --> 00:32:45.579
when you can't easily install fonts on your computer.

00:32:50.099 --> 00:32:52.540
Another big set of challenges.

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:58.380
I would love to know like the bits from my computer

00:32:58.380 --> 00:33:00.619
like being manually transmitted somewhere,

00:33:00.619 --> 00:33:01.979
that's why it takes so long.

00:33:04.099 --> 00:33:05.939
So one of the big differences

00:33:05.939 --> 00:33:10.380
between the way our packages work on Windows and Mac

00:33:10.380 --> 00:33:12.660
and Linux is that on Windows and Mac,

00:33:12.660 --> 00:33:15.739
when you install a package like XML2,

00:33:15.739 --> 00:33:18.540
which uses the libxmlc library,

00:33:18.540 --> 00:33:19.819
on Windows and Mac,

00:33:19.819 --> 00:33:23.219
libxml is like bundled inside that package.

00:33:23.219 --> 00:33:24.260
And you can just use it

00:33:24.260 --> 00:33:28.140
without having to separately worry about using libxml.

00:33:28.140 --> 00:33:31.060
Servers, generally, you're gonna install a package

00:33:31.060 --> 00:33:33.420
from source, which means you need to compile it,

00:33:33.420 --> 00:33:34.260
which means you need to have

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:36.219
all these additional bits of software

00:33:36.219 --> 00:33:39.020
installed on your computer.

00:33:39.020 --> 00:33:40.140
That's changing a little bit,

00:33:40.140 --> 00:33:41.900
like we've done a lot of work

00:33:41.900 --> 00:33:46.900
with PositPackageManager and PositPublicPackageManager,

00:33:47.739 --> 00:33:50.300
PositPublicPackageManager,

00:33:50.300 --> 00:33:52.020
to make this easier.

00:33:52.020 --> 00:33:54.780
And there's some great tools in the pack package,

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:57.020
which will tell you like all of the system dependencies

00:33:57.020 --> 00:33:58.660
that you need to install this package

00:33:58.660 --> 00:34:00.859
and all of its recursive dependencies,

00:34:00.859 --> 00:34:02.739
but tends to be a bit more painful

00:34:02.739 --> 00:34:04.180
and that might be something

00:34:04.180 --> 00:34:06.339
you need to get a server admin involved with.

00:34:06.339 --> 00:34:08.020
It's not something you can necessarily do

00:34:08.020 --> 00:34:09.300
by yourself anymore.

00:34:10.659 --> 00:34:12.860
On your laptop, you typically just install

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:15.179
all of your R packages in one library.

00:34:15.179 --> 00:34:16.979
Obviously, now on a shared server,

00:34:16.979 --> 00:34:18.620
you're gonna have lots of different libraries,

00:34:18.620 --> 00:34:21.060
because not everyone's gonna agree on that.

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:24.260
Similarly, it's a wild west on your laptop.

00:34:24.260 --> 00:34:25.739
You install packages from GitHub,

00:34:25.739 --> 00:34:26.699
you install them from CRAN,

00:34:26.699 --> 00:34:27.820
you install them from Bioconductor,

00:34:27.820 --> 00:34:30.139
you install them from like some random site

00:34:30.139 --> 00:34:31.459
you found on the internet.

00:34:32.340 --> 00:34:33.699
Hopefully on your central compute,

00:34:33.699 --> 00:34:36.300
that's gonna be a little bit more locked down.

00:34:39.419 --> 00:34:40.739
So that was kind of the transition

00:34:40.739 --> 00:34:43.020
from your laptop to central compute.

00:34:43.020 --> 00:34:45.860
There's another transition from central compute

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:47.379
to deployment.

00:34:47.379 --> 00:34:50.979
And that is you are no longer in an interactive environment.

00:34:50.979 --> 00:34:53.739
So when something goes wrong, when you get an error,

00:34:53.739 --> 00:34:56.820
you can no longer say, oh, give me a trace back,

00:34:56.820 --> 00:35:00.260
or let me browse into this function and fix it.

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:05.100
So debugging something that's failing

00:35:05.100 --> 00:35:09.219
on some other computer is extremely frustrating.

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:12.979
If you develop R packages,

00:35:12.979 --> 00:35:15.179
like the way you experience this often

00:35:15.179 --> 00:35:17.860
is that something fails in your automatic checks

00:35:17.860 --> 00:35:19.500
on GitHub Actions.

00:35:19.500 --> 00:35:22.820
And it fails in a way that you can't reproduce locally,

00:35:22.820 --> 00:35:24.699
and now your iteration speed,

00:35:24.699 --> 00:35:27.260
instead of like typing a few ideas of the console

00:35:27.260 --> 00:35:30.020
and getting them back in seconds,

00:35:30.020 --> 00:35:33.379
it's now like a 20 minute or a 30 minute loop,

00:35:33.379 --> 00:35:35.620
which is bad, not just because it's so long,

00:35:35.620 --> 00:35:37.620
but it's long enough that you do something else

00:35:37.620 --> 00:35:39.379
and then you forget about the thing you're trying to do

00:35:39.379 --> 00:35:41.620
and then you come back to it two hours later

00:35:41.620 --> 00:35:43.860
and you've lost all the state you had in your head.

00:35:43.860 --> 00:35:46.100
So there's definitely some like techniques

00:35:46.100 --> 00:35:46.939
that are different.

00:35:46.939 --> 00:35:49.179
Like when you move into a,

00:35:49.179 --> 00:35:51.739
when you're in an interactive debugging environment,

00:35:51.739 --> 00:35:55.179
it's all about like very quickly coming up with hypotheses

00:35:55.179 --> 00:35:57.580
about what's going wrong, testing them out,

00:35:57.580 --> 00:35:58.979
and then discarding them.

00:35:58.979 --> 00:36:01.780
And because you're in that short iteration cycle,

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:03.820
you can do that very simply.

00:36:03.820 --> 00:36:06.659
When you're in a batch scenario,

00:36:06.659 --> 00:36:09.739
it's more about like brainstorming every possible thing

00:36:09.739 --> 00:36:11.739
that could be causing this problem,

00:36:11.739 --> 00:36:13.899
trying to write some code that can identify

00:36:13.899 --> 00:36:17.699
all of those cases at once, and then deploying that

00:36:17.699 --> 00:36:21.060
so that when you get that information back in 20 minutes,

00:36:21.060 --> 00:36:23.139
you haven't just answered one possible question,

00:36:23.139 --> 00:36:26.219
you've answered like 10 possible questions.

00:36:26.219 --> 00:36:28.419
This is a little bit like if you've ever used,

00:36:28.459 --> 00:36:32.300
if you've ever used SAS to fit a linear model,

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:34.139
when you fit a model in SAS,

00:36:34.139 --> 00:36:37.860
it gives you back every single possible output

00:36:37.860 --> 00:36:40.459
that you could ever imagine doing to a model.

00:36:40.459 --> 00:36:42.459
And that is basically because when SAS was written,

00:36:42.459 --> 00:36:44.139
this was in the mainframe days,

00:36:44.139 --> 00:36:47.260
you would type out your SAS commands on a punch card,

00:36:47.260 --> 00:36:49.540
fit the model, and then like two hours later,

00:36:49.540 --> 00:36:50.939
you get the results.

00:36:50.939 --> 00:36:53.419
You don't wanna have to like wait another two hours

00:36:53.419 --> 00:36:55.820
to get some summary statistics on that model.

00:36:56.820 --> 00:36:58.820
And the other kind of technique

00:36:58.820 --> 00:37:01.459
that starts to get really useful is this idea of logging,

00:37:01.459 --> 00:37:04.939
just recording like what is happening in your code?

00:37:04.939 --> 00:37:06.459
Where have you got to?

00:37:06.459 --> 00:37:08.500
So when it goes wrong, you know,

00:37:08.500 --> 00:37:09.939
have you have some sense of like,

00:37:09.939 --> 00:37:11.379
how did I get to this point?

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:15.340
There's some certainly like really cool technologies

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:18.820
out there about like with time travel debugging,

00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:22.100
where it is theoretically possible in some languages

00:37:22.100 --> 00:37:26.060
to kind of capture a failure on a server

00:37:26.060 --> 00:37:28.459
and then bring it back to your local computer

00:37:28.459 --> 00:37:30.699
in a way that you can interactively debug.

00:37:30.699 --> 00:37:32.340
That seems like a dream,

00:37:33.659 --> 00:37:37.219
but not something that is easy to port to R, unfortunately.

00:37:38.379 --> 00:37:39.500
And then the other kind of issue

00:37:39.500 --> 00:37:43.179
with where this difference comes up

00:37:43.179 --> 00:37:45.939
is when you're authenticating against some server.

00:37:45.939 --> 00:37:48.820
Now, the easiest way and most,

00:37:48.820 --> 00:37:50.340
the way that works just about everywhere

00:37:50.340 --> 00:37:53.100
is to stuff credentials and environment variables.

00:37:53.979 --> 00:37:55.300
That works locally,

00:37:55.300 --> 00:37:57.100
that works in your deployment environment,

00:37:57.100 --> 00:37:59.020
that is all fine and dandy,

00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:01.699
but it is not really a great way to do off

00:38:01.699 --> 00:38:03.540
because a lot of these credentials

00:38:03.540 --> 00:38:06.100
ideally should be changing over time.

00:38:06.100 --> 00:38:07.219
They should be rotating

00:38:07.219 --> 00:38:08.979
and that means you need to update them.

00:38:08.979 --> 00:38:11.620
And if you've relied on like that password

00:38:11.620 --> 00:38:14.580
and like 15 different data science projects,

00:38:14.580 --> 00:38:17.379
now you're going to go through and update all 15 of those.

00:38:17.419 --> 00:38:20.540
So ideally, you're using something a bit more interactive,

00:38:20.540 --> 00:38:22.300
something like OAuth,

00:38:22.300 --> 00:38:24.780
where you're going to do like a little interactive dance

00:38:24.780 --> 00:38:27.699
to give the server some permission

00:38:27.699 --> 00:38:29.340
for you to do stuff on its behalf.

00:38:29.340 --> 00:38:31.620
It's going to give you something back interactively.

00:38:31.620 --> 00:38:34.260
This kind of all happens behind the scenes for you,

00:38:34.260 --> 00:38:38.060
all very easy to do interactively.

00:38:38.060 --> 00:38:39.780
But if you're doing this on a server,

00:38:39.780 --> 00:38:42.100
you can't do that kind of interactive dance.

00:38:42.100 --> 00:38:44.100
And that also forces you to think about,

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.179
well, like, who is doing this?

00:38:46.179 --> 00:38:48.620
Who is seeing this analysis?

00:38:48.620 --> 00:38:50.659
And typically, like if you're doing that locally,

00:38:50.659 --> 00:38:52.300
you are doing the analysis,

00:38:52.300 --> 00:38:53.540
you're going to pull down the data

00:38:53.540 --> 00:38:58.020
that you are allowed to see and work with that.

00:38:58.020 --> 00:39:00.060
If you're deploying something like a Shiny app,

00:39:00.060 --> 00:39:03.100
it's also possible that it should be using the data

00:39:03.100 --> 00:39:06.419
that the person viewing the Shiny app is allowed to see.

00:39:06.419 --> 00:39:08.179
I think that kind of the easiest scenario

00:39:08.179 --> 00:39:09.300
to think about this is like,

00:39:09.300 --> 00:39:11.739
if you're writing an HR app,

00:39:11.739 --> 00:39:14.300
like you should only be able to see the data

00:39:15.139 --> 00:39:17.379
for yourself and people report that report to you.

00:39:17.379 --> 00:39:18.780
You shouldn't be able to see random data

00:39:18.780 --> 00:39:21.179
for people in the organization.

00:39:21.179 --> 00:39:22.699
And this of course, like leads

00:39:22.699 --> 00:39:26.139
to the worst possible debugging scenario,

00:39:26.139 --> 00:39:28.540
which is bugs that only occur for other people

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:31.659
who can see data that you cannot see.

00:39:31.659 --> 00:39:34.379
And how you debug that, I have no idea,

00:39:34.379 --> 00:39:36.379
but thoughts and prayers.

00:39:38.060 --> 00:39:41.219
So today I'm going to talk about two of the three things

00:39:41.219 --> 00:39:43.739
that I think make something a production job

00:39:44.100 --> 00:39:45.899
that it's not run just once.

00:39:45.899 --> 00:39:48.020
And that causes these challenges

00:39:48.020 --> 00:39:49.340
that the schema might change,

00:39:49.340 --> 00:39:51.219
your dependencies might change,

00:39:51.219 --> 00:39:52.620
your platform might change,

00:39:52.620 --> 00:39:53.979
your uniforms might change,

00:39:53.979 --> 00:39:55.620
your requirements might change.

00:39:55.620 --> 00:39:57.820
And you need to think about these problems.

00:39:57.820 --> 00:39:59.540
Some of them have good solutions,

00:39:59.540 --> 00:40:01.300
some of them don't have good solutions,

00:40:01.300 --> 00:40:04.459
but at least I think acknowledging them is the first step.

00:40:05.500 --> 00:40:07.340
And then the other problem is

00:40:08.179 --> 00:40:09.780
that you're not just running it on your computer.

00:40:09.780 --> 00:40:12.580
You've got this transition possibly from Windows to Linux,

00:40:12.580 --> 00:40:15.739
from desktop to server, from interactive to batch,

00:40:15.739 --> 00:40:18.459
and you've got a bunch of challenges related to auth.

00:40:19.699 --> 00:40:21.139
I'll show you, I'll leave you with just like

00:40:21.139 --> 00:40:23.379
one last picture, which is my,

00:40:23.379 --> 00:40:25.540
sort of speaking to that last bullet point,

00:40:25.540 --> 00:40:28.219
that last problem, which is not just you,

00:40:28.219 --> 00:40:30.500
that now you're working with a team of data scientists

00:40:30.500 --> 00:40:32.780
and there's kind of this hierarchy of needs

00:40:32.780 --> 00:40:34.219
that ideally you want to be able to at least

00:40:34.219 --> 00:40:36.260
find your colleagues' work.

00:40:36.260 --> 00:40:39.500
Even better, you should be able to run their work.

00:40:40.500 --> 00:40:44.459
Even better, you should be able to understand their work.

00:40:45.860 --> 00:40:49.219
And optimally, you should actually be able to edit it

00:40:49.219 --> 00:40:51.699
if needed, so that if someone does leave your team,

00:40:51.699 --> 00:40:53.100
you can still go.

00:40:53.100 --> 00:40:57.659
I suspect many teams are still down here.

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:01.060
Some stream teams are like striving

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:02.540
to get higher up that pyramid,

00:41:02.540 --> 00:41:04.260
but definitely a challenge of

00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:06.139
how do you share work across people?

00:41:06.139 --> 00:41:08.780
How do you build standards in your team?

00:41:08.860 --> 00:41:10.219
Thank you.

